Introduction
In modern development, many applications need to react in real time to changes in the database. However, most solutions depend on those changes happening inside the application itself. But what if another system, a script, or even a console user modifies the data?
This is where Tentacolous comes in — a Spring Boot library that automatically executes Java methods when an INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE occurs in your tables, even if the change originates outside your application.
What makes Tentacolous different?

• Detects external changes: whether the modification comes from your API, another system, or an SQL script.

• Automatic infrastructure: creates functions, triggers, and an event table in PostgreSQL.

• Transparent integration: converts the JSON payload into your Java entity and executes the annotated method.

• Flexible configuration: define polling intervals, batch size, maximum attempts, and more.
Requirements

• Java 17+

• Spring Boot with a configured DataSource

• PostgreSQL for automatic trigger creation
Quick Example
Suppose you have an entity Person:
@Entity
@Table(name = "person")
public class Person {
@Id
@GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
private Long id;
private String name;
private String lastname;
private String email;
}With Tentacolous, you can react to inserts like this:
@UponInserting(entity = Person.class)
public void onPersonInserted(Person person) {
System.out.println("New record: " + person.getEmail());
}This method will automatically execute every time a new record is inserted into the person table, regardless of where the change comes from. In addition, you can also react to record modifications using the update or delete annotations:
@UponUpdating(entity = Person.class)
public void onPersonUpdated(Person person) {
System.out.println("Record updated: " + person.getEmail());
}@UponDeleting(entity = Person.class)
public void onPersonDeleted(Person person) {
System.out.println("Record deleted: " + person.getEmail());
}Installation
Add this dependency to your Maven pom.xml to access the library’s features:
<dependency>
<groupId>io.github.aimtone</groupId>
<artifactId>tentacolous</artifactId>
<version>0.1.6</version>
</dependency>Use Cases

• Real-time notifications: send an email or alert when a new user is inserted.

• Kafka integration: publish events to a topic when records are updated.

• Automatic auditing: log changes in sensitive tables.

• System synchronization: keep data consistent across applications.
Configuration in application.yml
tentacolous:
enabled: true
schema-management: auto
event-table: db_change_event
poll-interval: 1s
batch-size: 100
max-attempts: 3This allows Tentacolous to create and manage the necessary infrastructure in your database.
Conclusion
Tentacolous introduces a new way of working with database events in Spring Boot applications. Its simplicity and power make it an ideal tool for developers looking for reactivity, auditing, and synchronization without complexity.
